ORIGINAL = {
  "3": {
    "14": "<p><strong>ehyeh asher ehyeh</strong> (<em>ʾehyeh ʾăšer ʾehyeh</em>): 'I AM WHO I AM' or 'I WILL BE WHAT I WILL BE.' The divine name is derived from the verb <em>hayah</em> (to be). The Tetragrammaton (YHWH) is likely the Qal imperfect form of <em>hayah</em> — 'He is' or 'He will be.' The name declares YHWH's self-existence and sovereign freedom: he does not derive his existence from anything outside himself; his being is its own definition. John's seven I AM sayings (John 6:35; 8:12; 10:9, 11; 11:25; 14:6; 15:1) and the absolute 'I am' (John 8:58; 18:5-6) are deliberate invocations of the Exodus 3:14 name, claiming for the Son the same underived self-existence.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p><strong>kaved</strong> (<em>kābēd</em>, H3513): 'I have made heavy / hardened his heart.' The plague narrative employs three distinct Hebrew verbs for the hardening of Pharaoh's heart, each with a different shade of meaning: <strong>kaved</strong> (to be heavy, weighty — used of Pharaoh hardening his own heart in earlier plagues), <strong>chazaq</strong> (to be strong, firm — used most often when YHWH is the subject), and <strong>qashah</strong> (to be stiff, stubborn — rare, more extreme). The theological complexity is intentional: Pharaoh's hardness is simultaneously self-willed and divinely purposed. The purpose clause <em>lemaan siti ototi eleh beqirbo</em> ('that I may place these my signs in his midst') frames the entire plague cycle as a divine self-disclosure to Egypt, Israel, and all nations. Paul cites Exod 9:16 and ch. 4's pattern in Rom 9:17-18 to ground the doctrine of divine sovereignty in election.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>ulemaan tesapper beoznei vincha u-ven bincha</strong>: 'so that you may tell in the ears of your son and your son's son.' The generational transmission of the Exodus memory is a structural motif in the Torah: the plagues are not only acts of judgment but acts of testimony, performed so that the story can be told. <em>Sippur</em> (telling) is the root of the Passover Seder's <em>Haggadah</em> (telling/narrating). The phrase <em>hit'alalti</em> (I have dealt harshly, or I have made sport) uses a Hithpael reflexive form — YHWH does to Egypt what Egypt did to Israel. The table-turning theme is fundamental to the Exodus narrative's justice logic.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>anah lehathnot lifnai</strong>: 'refuse to humble yourself before me.' The Hiphil of <em>ana</em> (to humble, afflict) asks whether Pharaoh will submit to YHWH's sovereign authority. The same root (<em>ana</em>, H6031) is used for the affliction Israel suffered in Egypt (Exod 1:11-12) — YHWH now reverses the dynamic: the one who afflicted Israel is challenged to humble himself before YHWH. The refusal to humble oneself (<em>anah</em>) is the root sin of the Exodus: Pharaoh's <em>ge'ut</em> (pride) against YHWH's <em>kavod</em> (glory). James 4:10 and 1 Pet 5:6 ('Humble yourselves under God's mighty hand') draw on this vocabulary.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>arbeh</strong> (<em>ʾarbeh</em>, H697): locusts — from the root <em>rava</em> (to multiply, be numerous). The name itself evokes the swarm's characteristic: countless multitudes. Locusts in the ANE were the most feared agricultural catastrophe — they could strip a region of all vegetation in hours. Egyptian reliefs and texts document locust plagues as national disasters. Joel 1-2 uses the locust army as the primary image for YHWH's eschatological army of judgment. The eighth plague is the longest and most verbally elaborate of the plague accounts, with extensive dialogue between Moses and Pharaoh's officials.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>vichisa et-ein ha'aretz</strong>: 'they will cover the eye of the land' — a vivid idiom: <em>ein</em> (eye) here means the visible surface, the appearance. When the locusts cover the earth, the land's face cannot be seen. The same idiom appears in Num 22:5, 11, where the Israelites 'cover the eye of the land.' The completeness of the plague is emphasized: even what the hail (<em>barad</em>, plague 7) left behind will be devoured. The cumulative destruction of seven plagues on Egypt's agriculture is now being completed.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>umale'u vatecha u-vatei kol-avadecha</strong>: 'they will fill your palace and the houses of all your officials.' The locust invasion invades even the private dwellings — the inner sanctum of Egyptian society is not protected. <em>Melo</em> (fullness, filling) echoes YHWH's claim in Ps 24:1: 'The earth is YHWH's and its fullness (<em>umelo'ah</em>)' — the locusts, as YHWH's instrument, fill what YHWH owns. The emphasis on something 'your fathers and their fathers never saw since the day they came to this ground' establishes the unprecedented severity: the plagues exceed all historical memory.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>hayehi ha'ish moked lanu</strong>: 'Will this man be a snare/trap for us?' The noun <em>moked</em> (H4170) means a trap or snare, from the root meaning to ensnare. Pharaoh's own officials recognize the untenable situation: Egypt is being ruined (<em>avad</em>, perishing) for the sake of Pharaoh's stubbornness. The officials' intervention is the first crack in the Egyptian royal court's solidarity with Pharaoh. Their use of 'do you not yet know that Egypt is destroyed?' (<em>terem teda ki avdah mitzrayim</em>) employs a rhetorical question that functions as statement: Egypt is already ruined.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>mi vaʾmi haholchim</strong>: 'who and who are going?' — Pharaoh's interrogative is a negotiating tactic to limit which Israelites will worship. He will allow the men but not the women, children, or property. The exchange exposes the false nature of his offer: the worship of YHWH ('we will hold a festival to YHWH') requires the whole community — <em>uvizqenenu uvina'arenu bvanenu uvivnotenu uvetzoneinu uvivqarenu</em> (with our old and young, sons and daughters, flocks and herds). The pattern of partial concessions (ch. 8, 10) followed by retraction is a literary device showing the progressive hardening.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>bina'arenu u-vizqenenu nelech</strong>: 'with our young and old we will go.' Moses's response brooks no compromise: the entire community — every generation and all livestock — must participate in YHWH's festival. The totality requirement is theological: YHWH's worship is not a partial or partial-community activity. This prefigures the NT understanding that the gospel summons whole households (Acts 16:31-34), and that there is 'neither Jew nor Greek, slave nor free, male nor female' in Christ (Gal 3:28) — all are included.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>yihyeh YHWH imachem</strong>: 'May YHWH be with you — if I let you and your little ones go!' Pharaoh's sarcastic blessing becomes ironic: YHWH will indeed be with them, precisely by overcoming Pharaoh's opposition. <strong>Ra lifneichem</strong> ('evil/harm is before you') — Pharaoh accuses Moses of having evil intentions. The word <em>ra</em> (evil, harm) is the same word used in the Tree of Knowledge of good and evil (<em>tov vara</em>) — Pharaoh positions himself as the arbiter of good (staying in Egypt) and evil (going to worship).</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>vayegaresh otam meim pnei pharoh</strong>: 'and they were driven out from Pharaoh's presence' — the Piel of <em>garash</em> (to drive out, expel) is used: a forcible expulsion from Pharaoh's court. Moses and Aaron are expelled — the same verb used of expulsion from the garden in Gen 3:24 (<em>yigaresh</em>) and used of Israel's later expulsion from Canaan by its enemies. The expulsion from Pharaoh's presence is a bitter irony: Pharaoh drives out the only mediators who could end the plague.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>neteh yadcha al-eretz mitzrayim</strong>: 'stretch out your hand over the land of Egypt.' Moses's outstretched staff/hand is the recurring sign-gesture of YHWH's power acting through the human agent. Eight of the ten plagues involve Moses stretching out his staff or hand (exceptions: plagues 1, 5, 6). The gesture embodies the covenant relationship: YHWH acts <em>through</em> human agency, not apart from it. The raised hand of Moses in battle against Amalek (Exod 17:11) follows the same pattern — human gesture as conduit of divine power.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ruach qadim</strong> (east wind): the desert wind blowing from the east (Sinai, Arabia) — hot, dry, powerful, and in the ANE often understood as an ominous wind of divine judgment (cf. Hos 13:15: 'an east wind from YHWH will come'). The east wind drove the locusts overnight; when YHWH reversed it to a <em>ruach yam</em> (sea/west wind, v. 19), the locusts were swept into the Red Sea. YHWH controls both the natural forces and their direction — the plague and its removal are both divine acts.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>lifanav lo hayah khen arbeh</strong>: 'before him there was no such locust swarm' — the superlative formula (before never, after never) applied to the eighth plague echoes the same formula in Joel 2:2 ('there has been nothing like it before, nor will be again after it'). Joel's eschatological locust army uses the Exodus eighth plague as its type. The quantity description — <em>kaved meod</em> (very heavy, very severe) — links the plague severity to the vocabulary of the hardening (<em>kaved</em>): both Pharaoh's heart and the plague are described by the same root, as if the natural disaster bears the imprint of the spiritual condition that caused it.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>vayechashach ha'aretz</strong>: 'the land became dark' — the Hiphil of <em>chashach</em> (to be/become dark) is used; the locusts blackened the visible surface of the land. <em>Lo nivkah kol-yerek be'etz u-veesev hasadeh</em> ('nothing green remained on the trees or among the grasses of the field') — total agricultural devastation. Egypt's economy was agricultural; the Nile's annual flooding made Egypt the ancient world's breadbasket. Seven plagues targeting crops, livestock, and water systematically dismantled Egypt's food security.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>chataʾti l'YHWH eloheichem v'lachem</strong>: 'I have sinned against YHWH your God and against you.' The first explicit verbal confession of sin by Pharaoh — using the standard term <em>chata</em> (to sin, miss the mark, H2398). The dual object (against YHWH and against you) acknowledges both the vertical and horizontal dimensions of wrong. Pharaoh makes similar confessions in 9:27-28 and 10:16, but each time reverts after the plague is removed. The confessions without genuine repentance are a biblical illustration of the difference between remorse and repentance (<em>metanoia</em>) — the same distinction Paul draws in 2 Cor 7:10: 'worldly grief produces death.'</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>sa na chataʾti</strong>: 'please forgive my sin just this once' — the Qal imperative of <em>nasa</em> (to lift up, carry, forgive) with <em>na</em> (please, particle of entreaty). The idiom <em>nasa chet</em> (lift/carry sin) is the standard Hebrew for forgiveness; YHWH is the one who &ldquo;lifts up&rdquo; sin (Exod 34:7; Num 14:18; Ps 32:5). Pharaoh's request uses exactly the right theological vocabulary — but the subsequent verse shows the hardened heart persisting after the plague's removal. Prayer for relief during judgment without transformation afterward is one of the plague narrative's defining themes.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>vayetze meim pharoh vayitpallel el-YHWH</strong>: 'he went out from Pharaoh and prayed to YHWH.' Moses's intercession for Pharaoh — despite Pharaoh's persistent wickedness — is a remarkable act of prophetic intercession. Moses functions here as a type of the Christological intercessor: praying for oppressors who continue to resist (Luke 23:34: 'Father, forgive them'). The verb <em>palal</em> (Hithpael: to pray, intercede) becomes the standard term for intercessory prayer throughout the OT.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>ruach yam chazaq meod</strong>: 'a very strong west wind' (<em>ruach yam</em>, literally sea-wind). YHWH reverses the wind direction to remove the locusts: what he sent by east wind he removes by west wind. The locusts are cast into the <em>yam suf</em> (Red Sea/Sea of Reeds) — the same body of water Israel will cross and Egypt will drown in. The sea that drowns the locusts will drown Pharaoh's army. YHWH's complete control over the natural world is the implicit theology: storm, wind, sea — all serve as instruments of his judgment and deliverance.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>vayechazzeq YHWH et-lev paroh</strong>: 'YHWH strengthened Pharaoh's heart' — the Piel of <em>chazaq</em> (to strengthen, make firm, harden). This is the most common verb used when YHWH is the agent of the hardening. The three-verb hardening vocabulary of the plague narrative (<em>kaved</em>, <em>chazaq</em>, <em>qashah</em>) represents a progression: Pharaoh hardened his own heart first (chs. 7-9); YHWH then confirms and strengthens that hardening as judgment. Paul's use of Exod 9:16 in Rom 9:17 grounds the doctrine that divine sovereignty operates through human choices, not apart from them — God's hardening of Pharaoh is the judicial confirmation of Pharaoh's own self-hardening.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>veyamesh choshech</strong>: 'a darkness that may be felt/groped' — a hapax phrase using <em>mamash</em> (to touch, feel). The darkness of the ninth plague is physically tangible: not merely absence of light but a positive, material quality. Exodus Rabbah connects this to the primordial <em>tohu</em> (formlessness) of Gen 1:2: 'the earth was formless and dark (<em>choshech</em>).' YHWH's darkness-plague reverses creation's order — three days of uncreation precede the death of Egypt's firstborn. The number three echoes the three days of creation's light-establishment (Gen 1:3-13). The darkness-to-light pattern is the foundation of Paul's new creation language: 'God who said &ldquo;let light shine out of darkness&rdquo; has shone in our hearts' (2 Cor 4:6).</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>vayehiy choshech-afelah bechol-eretz mitzrayim shloshet yamim</strong>: 'there was a thick darkness in all the land of Egypt for three days.' The double term <em>choshech afelah</em> (darkness of thick/pitchy darkness) intensifies beyond ordinary darkness into absolute deprivation of light. Egyptians worshiped Ra the sun-god as their supreme deity — three days of total darkness were a direct assault on the supreme Egyptian god. The ninth plague is among the most theologically pointed: YHWH claims dominion over the very light that Egypt considered divine. The parallel darkness at the crucifixion (Matt 27:45: 'darkness over all the land from the sixth to the ninth hour') deliberately evokes this plague — judgment-darkness at the moment of the new covenant Passover.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>ulekhol benei Yisrael hayah or bimoshvotam</strong>: 'but all the Israelites had light in their dwelling places.' The light/darkness contrast between Israel and Egypt is a pattern throughout the plagues: YHWH makes a distinction (<em>hafla</em>) between his people and Egypt. The dwelling places (<em>moshvotam</em>) of Israel are illuminated while Egypt gropes. This pattern appears in the Passover night itself (12:23: the destroyer does not enter Israel's blood-marked homes) and ultimately in Revelation's new Jerusalem: 'the city has no need of sun or moon, for the glory of God gives it light' (Rev 21:23).</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>rak tzoneichem u-vaqarchem yutztav</strong>: 'only your flocks and herds shall be left behind.' Pharaoh's fourth concession offer: go with your families, but leave your animals. Moses refuses because the animals are needed for the sacrifices — <em>ki mimenu nikach la'avod et-YHWH eloheinu</em> ('from them we will take to serve YHWH our God'). The animals belong to the worship of YHWH; to leave them in Egypt is to keep the means of sacrifice captive. Moses's insistence that <em>lo tippalter parsa</em> ('not a hoof shall be left') is a declaration that YHWH's worship requires total mobilization of resources — nothing can remain in bondage.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>gam atah titen beyadenu zevachim ve'olot</strong>: 'you yourself must provide us with sacrifices and burnt offerings to present to YHWH our God.' Moses turns the tables: not only will Israel take their own livestock, but Pharaoh must contribute to the sacrifices. The demand illustrates the comprehensive reversal: Egypt's wealth will fund Israel's worship of YHWH. This prefigures the spoiling of Egypt (Exod 12:35-36) and the NT pattern of earthly resources being redirected to the service of God's kingdom.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>vegam miqnenenu yelech imanu lo tishar parsa</strong>: 'our livestock will also go with us; not a hoof will be left.' The idiom <em>lo tishar parsa</em> (not a hoof shall remain) became a proverbial expression for complete exit/departure. The explanation given — we don't know what YHWH will require until we arrive — is theologically important: worship cannot be planned in advance from a posture of compromise with slavery. Full exodus precedes authentic worship. This anti-negotiation principle runs through the NT: the gospel does not accommodate gradual partial repentance; it calls for complete reorientation.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>vayechazzeq YHWH et-lev paroh</strong>: The tenth hardening reference in the plague narrative. The alternation between self-hardening (Pharaoh's own choice) and divine hardening (YHWH confirming the pattern) is now nearing its climax: the next plague will be decisive. The repeated hardening-and-reprieve cycle illustrates what Hebrews warns against: the danger of continued exposure to divine truth producing not softening but increased hardness (Heb 3:7-8: 'Today if you hear his voice do not harden your hearts'; 3:13: 'hardened through the deceitfulness of sin').</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>hishamer lecha al-tosef reot panai</strong>: 'guard yourself, do not see my face again.' The Niphal reflexive/passive of <em>shamar</em> (to guard, keep) used reflexively: 'guard yourself.' Pharaoh's threat carries irony: he is the one who should guard himself against YHWH. The prohibition of seeing Moses's face mirrors the earlier encounter where Moses could not see YHWH's face (Exod 33:20) — but the roles are reversed: a mortal potentate threatens the prophet of YHWH. Pharaoh's final rejection of Moses will be met by the final plague — the death of the firstborn.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>ken dibarta</strong>: 'you have spoken correctly/rightly.' Moses affirms Pharaoh's statement — he will indeed never see Pharaoh's face again. The Hebrew <em>ken</em> (thus, rightly) is emphatic. Moses's departure is a prophetic symbolic act: the prophet's withdrawal from the king signals the withdrawal of divine grace and the inauguration of the final judgment. This scene closes the plague-cycle's dialogue phase; the tenth plague will require no further negotiation.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p><strong>nega echad od</strong>: 'one plague more' — literally 'one stroke/blow still.' The word <em>nega</em> (H5061, plague, blow, stroke) is used throughout Leviticus for skin diseases but here describes the final divine blow. The phrase <em>acharei ken</em> ('after that') signals the definitive end: after this plague Pharaoh will not merely let Israel go but drive them out (<em>garash</em>) — the expulsion will be total and urgent. YHWH's control over the timing ('I will bring') is emphasized: the final plague waits on YHWH's initiative, not Pharaoh's decision.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>veyishalu ish meyit reyahu veisha meyit reutah keli-keseph u-chelei zahav</strong>: 'each man shall ask of his neighbor and each woman of her neighbor articles of silver and gold.' The verb <em>sha'al</em> (H7592, to ask, borrow, request) is used — the same verb behind the Sheol wordplay in OT (sheol = place of asking/seeking?) and behind Samuel's name. Israel is instructed to ask/borrow the Egyptians' valuables. Exod 12:36 will describe the fulfillment: they &ldquo;plundered&rdquo; (<em>vayenatzlu</em>, Piel of <em>natsal</em>, to strip/plunder) Egypt. The plundering of Egypt was the original fulfillment of YHWH's promise to Abraham that Israel would leave with 'great possessions' (Gen 15:14).</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>vayiten YHWH et-chen ha'am beynei Mitzrayim</strong>: 'YHWH gave the people favor in the eyes of the Egyptians.' The noun <em>chen</em> (H2580, favor, grace, charm) — YHWH sovereignly disposed the Egyptians to view the Israelites favorably, so that they would willingly give their valuables. The same <em>chen</em> vocabulary describes Joseph's favor in Egypt (Gen 39:4), Moses himself before Pharaoh (Exod 11:3: <em>gadol meod beynei avdei pharoh u-veynei ha'am</em>), and ultimately God's favor on believers in the NT (Luke 1:30; Acts 2:47). Divine favor is not earned by the recipient but given by YHWH to accomplish his purposes.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>kachatzot halaylah</strong>: 'about midnight' — the time of maximum darkness and vulnerability. The phrase <em>kachatzot</em> uses the preposition <em>ke-</em> (like, approximately) — either &ldquo;about midnight&rdquo; or a divine approximation. Rabbinic tradition debated whether this was exactly midnight (YHWH's clock is precise) or approximately (human calculation is imprecise). The midnight setting is theologically rich: the darkest hour of the darkest plague is YHWH's appointed time. The Passover night's midnight becomes the paradigm for the eschatological night-watch: 'the bridegroom comes at midnight' (Matt 25:6).</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>kol bekhor beeretz mitzrayim yamut</strong>: 'every firstborn in Egypt shall die.' The scope is total: from <em>bekhor par'oh hayoshev al-kis'o</em> (the firstborn of Pharaoh on his throne) to <em>bekhor hashifchah asher achar harechayim</em> (the firstborn of the slave-girl behind the millstones) to the firstborn of animals. The tenth plague targets the <em>bekhor</em> (firstborn, H1060) — the one who bears the legal primogeniture rights and the one who carries the family line. Egypt's future, from throne to stable, is struck. The logic: Egypt enslaved Israel, YHWH's firstborn son (Exod 4:22-23: &ldquo;Israel is my son, my firstborn; let my son go&rdquo;), so YHWH strikes Egypt's firstborn.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>vehayetah tzeaqah gedolah bechol-eretz mitzrayim</strong>: 'there will be a great cry throughout all the land of Egypt.' The word <em>tzeaqah</em> (H6818, cry, outcry) is used for the cry of the oppressed: it is the <em>tzeaqat</em> Sodom that rose to YHWH (Gen 18:20), and it is the cry of Israel under slavery that YHWH heard (Exod 3:7: <em>vaeshma et-tzaakatam</em>). The same cry Israel made under oppression is now reversed and falls on Egypt. The <em>tzeaqah</em> motif in the OT establishes that YHWH hears the cry of the oppressed — and his justice eventually turns oppressor and oppressed.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>ul'chol benei Yisrael lo yecheratz kelev leshono</strong>: 'but to all the Israelites not even a dog shall move its tongue.' The idiom <em>lo yecheratz kelev leshono</em> ('no dog will sharpen/whet its tongue') describes complete silence and calm among Israel during the plague. The contrast is stark: Egypt's <em>tzeaqah gedolah</em> (great cry) vs. Israel's silence. <strong>Yafle YHWH</strong> ('YHWH will work wonders/distinctions') — the verb <em>palah</em> (H6395, to distinguish, separate, make wonderful) is the key term for YHWH's covenant distinction between Israel and Egypt throughout the plagues. The same distinction that protected Israel from the plagues now preserves them through the final judgment.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>veyardu kol-avadecha eleh elai vehishtachavu-li</strong>: 'and all these servants of yours will come down to me and bow down to me.' Moses's prophecy is precise: Pharaoh himself will not bow, but his officials will come begging. <strong>Bechemah gedolah</strong> ('in great anger') — Moses's departure from Pharaoh's presence in great anger (<em>af</em>, H639, anger, nose) is the only place in the plague narrative where Moses's emotional state is described. The prophet's righteous anger at Pharaoh's persistent hardness mirrors divine anger (cf. Mark 3:5: Jesus looked at the Pharisees with anger at their hardness of heart).</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>lema'an revot moftai beEretz Mitzrayim</strong>: 'in order that my wonders may be multiplied in Egypt.' The purpose (<em>lema'an</em>) clause here provides the theological framework for the entire plague cycle: the plagues are not only punitive but revelatory. The multiplication (<em>revot</em>, Qal infinitive of <em>ravah</em>) of wonders serves divine self-disclosure. <em>Moftim</em> (H4159, wonders, signs) is paired with <em>otot</em> (signs) throughout the Exodus narrative (7:3; 11:9-10) to describe the plagues as the definitive divine testimony to YHWH's incomparable power. The NT uses the same <em>semeia kai terata</em> (signs and wonders) vocabulary for Jesus's miracles and the apostolic ministry (Acts 2:43; 5:12; Heb 2:4).</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>vaMoshe veAharon asu et-kol-hamoftim haeleh lifnei par'oh</strong>: 'Moses and Aaron did all these wonders before Pharaoh.' This verse summarizes the entire plague narrative (chs. 7-11) before the Passover account. The repeated summary also marks the transition: the <em>moftim</em> performed before Pharaoh are now complete; what follows is the pivotal final act. <strong>Vayechazzeq YHWH et-lev par'oh</strong> — the final hardening before the final plague. The summary formula has appeared ten times through the plague narrative; this last occurrence closes the loop and prepares for the Passover night.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p><strong>vayomer YHWH el-Moshe veEl-Aharon beEretz Mitzrayim</strong>: 'YHWH said to Moses and Aaron in Egypt.' The address to both Moses and Aaron (rather than Moses alone relaying to Aaron) elevates the Passover instruction to the highest level of direct divine command. The phrase <em>beEretz Mitzrayim</em> ('in Egypt') is emphasized — this command is given while Israel is still in the land of bondage, before the exodus. The Passover ritual is thus defined as an act performed within the context of redemption-in-progress, not retrospectively from safety.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>hachodesh hazeh lachem rosh chadashim</strong>: 'this month shall be for you the beginning of months.' YHWH resets the calendar: the month of the Passover (Nisan/Abib, spring) becomes the first month of Israel's sacred year. The calendar reset is a statement of sovereignty: YHWH defines time itself for his covenant people. The phrase <em>lachem</em> ('for you') is emphatic — this new calendar belongs to Israel specifically, as a testimony of their redemption. The year now begins with the Passover, encoding the memory of redemption into the very structure of time.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>seh l'vet avot</strong>: 'a lamb/kid per household' (<em>seh</em>, H7716, small cattle — either sheep or goat, as v. 5 clarifies). The Passover is organized by households (<em>beit avot</em>, ancestral households) — not individuals, not the national assembly, but family units. The Passover is fundamentally a family meal, a household ceremony. This household structure is fundamental to the transmission of the covenant narrative to each generation (v. 26-27) and becomes foundational to the NT's household-church model (Acts 16:31-34: &ldquo;believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved, you and your household&rdquo;).</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>ufikku ish lefal ochlo</strong>: 'you shall count/divide up according to each person's eating.' The calculation principle (<em>puk</em>, to calculate, count) requires each household to estimate how many people can consume a whole lamb and share with neighbors if needed. The quantitative precision — every person counted, nothing wasted — reflects the covenantal seriousness of the Passover. <em>Lifal ochlo</em> (lit. 'according to the mouth of eating') uses the body-part metonymy <em>peh</em> (mouth) for eating. The communal sharing principle ensures no one is excluded for practical reasons.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>seh tamim</strong> (<em>śeh tāmîm</em>): 'a lamb without blemish' — the Passover lamb must be <em>tamim</em> (perfect, without defect), the sacrificial standard that applies to all Levitical offerings (Lev 22:19-20) and is applied to Christ in 1 Pet 1:19: 'without blemish or spot.' The lamb is also <em>ben shanah</em> (in its first year), symbolically in the prime of life — not old and worn out. The NT applies the typology systematically: Christ is the Passover lamb (1 Cor 5:7), his bones were not broken per Exod 12:46 (John 19:36), and his blood marks and protects the new covenant community.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>ben haarbayim</strong>: 'between the two evenings' — a precise but debated temporal notation. The Pharisees understood it as between sunset (the first evening, when the sun goes down) and nightfall (the second evening, when darkness is complete) — roughly 3:00–5:00 PM. The Sadducees took it as between afternoon and sunset. The Synoptic Gospels place the Last Supper on the Passover night; John places the crucifixion on the day of Passover preparation (John 19:14) — Jesus dying as the lambs were being slaughtered. The timing of Christ's death aligns with the <em>ben haarbayim</em> slaughter of the Passover lamb.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>velaqchu min-hadam venatenu al-shtei hamezuzot veal-hamashqof</strong>: 'they shall take some of the blood and put it on the two doorposts and the lintel.' The <em>mezuzot</em> (doorposts, from <em>mezuzah</em>, pillar/post) and <em>mashqof</em> (lintel, top of the doorframe) become the site of the blood application. The hyssop applicator (v. 22) and the blood-on-wood pattern anticipate the cross's blood-application to the wooden frame. The verb <em>natan</em> (to give/place) used for putting blood on the doorposts is the same verb used for YHWH's giving of signs and covenants — the blood-sign is an act of covenant protection.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>kal-maror</strong> (bitter herbs): <em>maror</em> (H4844, bitterness) — the bitter herbs of the Passover meal encode the memory of slavery's bitterness (<em>vaymareiru et-chayeihem</em>, 'they made their lives bitter,' Exod 1:14). <em>Matzot</em> (unleavened bread, H4682): bread made without leaven (<em>chametz</em>), baked in haste. Paul explains the significance in 1 Cor 5:7-8: '<em>chametz</em>' (leaven) = malice and evil; <em>matzot</em> (unleavened bread) = sincerity and truth. The Passover meal contains its own theological interpretation encoded in its ingredients: the bitterness of slavery, the haste of redemption, the purity required for the new beginning.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>tzali-esh</strong>: 'roasted over fire' — not raw (<em>na</em>) and not boiled in water (<em>mevushal bamayim</em>). The specific requirement for fire-roasting distinguishes the Passover preparation from the standard Israelite cooking method (boiling) and from raw consumption. Fire in the OT is associated with divine holiness and judgment (Gen 3:24; Exod 3:2; 19:18). The fire-roasted lamb is thus associated with YHWH's presence and glory. The specific prohibition against boiling may have also distinguished Israel's practice from Egyptian or Canaanite religious cooking customs.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>lo totiru mimenu ad-boker</strong>: 'you shall not leave any of it until morning.' The Passover lamb must be consumed entirely in a single night — nothing stored, nothing saved. The remainder must be burned (<em>ushvarti ba'esh</em>). The prohibition against leftovers has two functions: (1) the lamb is a sacred meal, not ordinary food to be treated casually; (2) the meal commemorates the haste of the exodus — they would leave by morning. The fire-disposal of the remainder also ensures no carcass remains to be desecrated. The totality of consumption pictures the completeness of Christ's atoning work: nothing left incomplete.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>pesach hu l'YHWH</strong>: 'it is the Passover of YHWH.' The noun <em>pesach</em> (H6453) is derived from the verb <em>pasach</em> (v. 13, 23: 'to pass over/protect'). The traditional interpretation: YHWH &ldquo;passed over&rdquo; the blood-marked houses. More nuanced readings suggest <em>pasach</em> means to &ldquo;protect&rdquo; or &ldquo;hover over&rdquo; (cf. Isa 31:5: 'like birds hovering, so YHWH of hosts will protect Jerusalem') rather than merely &ldquo;skip past.&rdquo; <strong>Bechipazon</strong> (in haste, H2649) — the posture of readiness: loins girded, sandals on feet, staff in hand. The Passover meal is eaten as people on the move, not at leisure. The eschatological dimension: the meal anticipates departure from the present age.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>veavarti beEretz Mitzrayim balaylah hazeh</strong>: 'I will pass through Egypt on this night.' YHWH acts in the first person — no angel is mentioned as the agent (contrast the &ldquo;destroyer&rdquo; of v. 23). The Piel of <em>avar</em> (to pass through, cross over) with YHWH as subject is the most direct form of divine personal action in the plague narrative. <strong>Ubechol-elohei Mitzrayim e'eseh shefatim</strong>: 'against all the gods of Egypt I will execute judgments.' The plagues are explicitly identified as judgments against Egypt's gods — each plague targets a deity of the Egyptian pantheon: the Nile (Hapi), the sun (Ra/Khepri), life-force (various animal deities). The tenth plague kills the Pharaoh's heir — the incarnation of the divine Horus. YHWH alone is <em>Elohim</em>.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>vehayah hadam lachem l'ot</strong>: 'the blood shall be a sign for you on the houses.' <em>Ot</em> (H226, sign, token) is the same word used for the covenant signs of rainbow (Gen 9:12-13) and circumcision (Gen 17:11). The blood-sign on the doorposts is the Passover covenant-sign — the external mark of covenant protection. <strong>Ufasachti aleichem</strong>: 'I will pass over/protect you' — the verb <em>pasach</em> (H6452) used in the Qal perfect. YHWH sees the blood and acts protectively. The NT parallel: the blood of Christ applied to the believer is the new covenant sign of protection from divine judgment (Rom 3:25: <em>hilasterion</em>; 1 Cor 5:7: Christ our Passover lamb has been sacrificed).</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>zikaron</strong> (H2146, memorial, remembrance): 'this day shall be a memorial for you.' The Passover is designed as a <em>zikaron</em> — an act of sacred memory that makes the past event present for each generation. Deuteronomy 16's Passover instructions emphasize <em>zachor</em> (remember) as the primary obligation. The Last Supper's command <em>touto poieite eis ten emen anamnesin</em> ('do this in remembrance of me,' Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:24-25) uses the Greek <em>anamnesis</em>, the exact LXX translation of <em>zikaron</em>. The Eucharist is the new Passover <em>zikaron</em> — the memorial that makes the new exodus present for the covenant community in each generation.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>chametz</strong> (H2557, leaven, leavened bread): to be removed from houses for seven days. The Feast of Unleavened Bread begins the day after Passover and continues for seven days (vv. 15-20). <em>Chametz</em> is the fermenting agent — it causes bread to rise through a process of decomposition. Paul's interpretation (1 Cor 5:6-8) applies <em>chametz</em> as a metaphor for moral corruption: 'a little leaven leavens the whole lump; therefore cleanse out the old leaven that you may be a new lump, as you really are unleavened. For Christ our Passover has been sacrificed.' The seven-day removal of leaven pictures the complete moral renewal that accompanies redemption.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>miqra-kodesh</strong> (H4744, sacred assembly, holy convocation): 'a holy convocation on the first and seventh days.' <em>Miqra</em> is derived from <em>qara</em> (to call, summon) — the assembly is called by YHWH. The sacred assemblies frame the week-long festival. <em>Lo-ta'asu vo melacha</em> ('no work shall be done') — the restriction on labor marks the day as set apart for YHWH's purposes, not human labor. The exception: food preparation (<em>asher ye'achel lechol nefesh</em>) is permitted, grounding the sacred in the physical necessity of eating — the festival is embodied, not merely spiritual.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>ushemartem et-hamatzot</strong>: 'you shall guard the unleavened bread / observe the Festival of Unleavened Bread.' The Qal perfect of <em>shamar</em> (H8104, to keep, guard, observe) — the same verb used for keeping the Sabbath and the covenant. <em>Kiy beetzem hayom hazeh hotzeti et-tzivoteichem</em>: 'on this very day I brought your armies out of Egypt.' <em>Tzivot</em> (armies, hosts) — Israel in the exodus is framed as YHWH's military force. The same language — <em>Tzivot YHWH</em> (the armies of YHWH) — appears in v. 41. The exodus is not a refugee escape but a military march of YHWH's forces.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>beavirim ad-esrim veechad lachodesh</strong>: 'from the evening of the fourteenth to the twenty-first.' The Feast of Unleavened Bread begins on the evening of the fourteenth (when the Passover lamb is eaten) and continues until the twenty-first — seven full days. The precision of the calendar dates reflects the covenantal seriousness: the times are YHWH's appointed times (<em>moedim</em>), not flexible traditions. <em>Erev ad-erev</em> (evening to evening) reflects the Hebrew reckoning of days from sunset to sunset (Gen 1:5 pattern), the same principle underlying the Sabbath.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>kol-se'or lo yimmatze bevatechem</strong>: 'no leaven shall be found in your houses' — the command escalates from removing leaven (v. 15) to ensuring none is even present. The thoroughness of the pre-Passover leaven search (<em>bedikat chametz</em>) became one of Judaism's most detailed ritual observances. <em>Ger u-vezrach ha'aretz</em> ('both for the foreigner and for the native of the land'): the rule applies equally to resident aliens and native Israelites. The equal application to <em>gerim</em> (resident foreigners) anticipates the NT abolition of ethnic distinctions within the covenant community.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>kol-machmat lo tochelu</strong>: 'eat nothing leavened.' The prohibition is absolute and repeated for emphasis throughout the chapter. The seven-day period of unleavened bread was so central to Israelite identity that <em>chametz</em> became a theological symbol. The Qumran community's strict unleavened-bread practice and Paul's application to moral purity (1 Cor 5:7-8) both reflect the deep symbolic resonance of the <em>chametz/matzot</em> opposition — corruption vs. purity, old age vs. new creation.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>mishchu uqechu lachem seh lemishpechotechem</strong>: 'draw/select and take a lamb for your families.' Moses now communicates YHWH's instructions to the elders of Israel — the chain of authority flows: YHWH → Moses → elders → people. The Qal imperative <em>mishchu</em> (draw out, select) specifically means to draw/choose from the flock — a deliberate act of selection. The communal family-centered instruction reinforces the household structure of the Passover. Moses instructs Israel to &ldquo;slaughter the Passover lamb&rdquo; (<em>vesachatu hapasach</em>) — the lamb's slaughter is identified with the feast itself.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>ezov</strong> (H231, hyssop): a small bushy plant with absorbent properties used in purification rituals throughout the OT (Lev 14:4-6, 49-52; Num 19:6, 18; Ps 51:7). The hyssop branch dipped in the basin of blood and applied to the doorframes is the original ritual use of this plant. Its later purification associations (Ps 51:7: 'purge me with hyssop and I shall be clean') ground the Passover blood-application in the broader purity theology. John 19:29 places a hyssop branch in the scene of Jesus's crucifixion — a deliberate echo of the Passover hyssop application.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>hamashchit</strong> (H4889, the destroyer): 'YHWH will not allow the destroyer to enter your houses.' The <em>mashchit</em> (destroyer, from <em>shachat</em>, to destroy, corrupt) appears here as the agent of the final plague — distinct from YHWH himself acting directly (v. 12). Hebrews 11:28 summarizes: 'By faith he kept the Passover and sprinkled the blood, so that the Destroyer of the firstborn might not touch them.' The <em>mashchit</em> is the same figure as the 'destroying angel' in later texts (2 Sam 24:16; 1 Chr 21:15). The blood on the doorpost stops the destroyer — it is the visible covenant sign that marks the household as YHWH's.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>ushemertem et-hadavar hazeh lechok lecha ulvaneicha ad-olam</strong>: 'keep this word as a statute for you and your children forever.' The Passover is not merely historical commemoration but perpetual covenant obligation — <em>lechok olam</em> (an eternal statute). The generational instruction follows in vv. 26-27: the children's question and the parent's answer are built into the ritual, ensuring the narrative is transmitted. The question-and-answer structure of the Passover became the template for catechetical instruction throughout Israel's covenant history.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>vahayah ki tavo'u el-ha'aretz</strong>: 'when you enter the land.' The Passover instruction looks forward to the land — it is given in Egypt but oriented toward Canaan. The future tense (<em>tavo'u</em>) frames the current captivity within a trajectory of promise and fulfillment. <em>Ushmartem et-ha'avoda hazot</em> ('you shall keep this service/worship') — the word <em>avoda</em> (H5656, service, work, worship) was used for Israel's slavery in Egypt and is now redirected: the same word describes Israel's worship-service to YHWH. Redemption from slavery transforms <em>avoda</em> from oppression to devotion.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>vehayah ki yomeru aleichem bneichem</strong>: 'when your children say to you...' The intergenerational transmission of the Passover narrative is built into the covenant structure: children will ask, parents will answer. The Haggadah's four sons (the wise, the wicked, the simple, and the one who does not know how to ask) are rabbinic elaborations of this built-in catechetical question. The Passover's narrative structure — question, answer, story — becomes the template for Christian kerygmatic preaching: the gospel is proclaimed in response to questions generated by covenant signs (baptism, Eucharist).</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>zevach pesach hu l'YHWH</strong>: 'it is the Passover sacrifice to YHWH.' The answer to the children's question names the meal as a <em>zevach</em> (sacrifice, offering) — the Passover is not merely a family dinner but a sacrificial act. <em>Asher pasach al-batei vnei Yisrael beMitzrayim</em> ('who passed over the houses of Israel in Egypt') — the explanation links the meal to the original event it commemorates. <em>Vayiqod ha'am vayishtachavu</em> ('the people bowed down and worshiped') — the response to the instruction is worship, not merely compliance. The Passover narrative evokes awe and gratitude before it demands observance.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>vayelechu vaya'asu benei Yisrael ka'asher tzivah YHWH</strong>: 'the Israelites went and did exactly as YHWH had commanded.' The compliance formula (<em>ka'asher tzivah YHWH</em>, 'as YHWH commanded') appears repeatedly throughout Exodus (cf. chs. 39-40 re. the tabernacle). The formula marks covenant faithfulness: Israel's obedience to the precise Passover instructions is the covenant act that activates the divine protection. The collective obedience of the community (<em>benei Yisrael</em>, sons of Israel) stands as a model of covenant response — hearing and doing.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>vayehiy bechatzot halaylah</strong>: 'at midnight' — the fulfillment of Moses's prophetic announcement (11:4). The precision of the fulfillment — at the exact time YHWH announced — validates the prophetic word. <em>Vayak YHWH kol-bechor beeretz Mitzrayim</em>: 'YHWH struck every firstborn in Egypt' — the Hiphil of <em>nakah</em> (H5221, to strike, smite) with YHWH as subject. The tenth plague requires no naturalistic explanation: it is direct divine action at the announced time. The scope — from Pharaoh's throne to the prisoner in the dungeon to the livestock — demonstrates YHWH's sovereignty over every social stratum of Egypt.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>vataqom hu vechol-avadav vechol-Mitzrayim laylah</strong>: 'he arose in the night, he and all his officials and all Egypt.' The national night-rising echoes the earlier plagues (8:20: Pharaoh arose early) but this time there is no negotiation — only <em>tzeaqah gedolah</em> (great cry). <em>Ki-ein bayit asher ein-sham met</em>: 'for there was not a house where there was no one dead' — the totality of the judgment is emphasized. The Egyptian household cry mirrors Israel's cry under slavery (Exod 2:23; 3:7). YHWH has heard the cry of his people and now Egypt experiences the cry of the bereaved.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>qumu tze'u mitoch ammi</strong>: 'rise up, go out from among my people.' Pharaoh's night summons to Moses and Aaron ends with what he refused for ten plagues: 'go, serve YHWH as you have said.' <em>Gam-tzoneichem gam-biqrechem qechu ka'asher dibartem</em>: 'even your flocks and your herds, take as you have spoken' — every condition Moses demanded is conceded in a single sentence. <em>Uvelachtem gam oti</em>: 'and bless me also' — Pharaoh now asks a blessing from the man he commanded to leave his presence never to return (10:28). The reversal is complete: the oppressor becomes the petitioner.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>uvelachtem gam oti</strong>: 'bless me also.' Pharaoh's request for blessing from Moses — whom he had threatened with death on sight (10:28) — is the ultimate reversal of the power dynamic. <em>Varets vatekeved al-ha'am</em> ('the Egyptians urged the people, pressing them urgently') — the very Egyptians who enslaved Israel now cannot expel them fast enough. The verb <em>chazaq</em> (to be strong, urge strongly) used of the Egyptians' urging echoes the <em>chazaq</em> of Pharaoh's hardened heart — the strength that held Israel captive is now directed toward releasing them.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>vatechez Mitzrayim al-ha'am lemahher leshalcham min-ha'aretz</strong>: 'Egypt urged the people to hurry, to send them out of the land.' <em>Ki amru kulanu meitim</em>: 'for they said, &ldquo;we are all dying.&rdquo;' The Egyptians' fear of total annihilation drives the urgency. The reversal is stark: Israel came to Egypt as seventy people fleeing famine (Gen 46:27); they leave as a nation of 600,000 men (v. 37), bearing Egypt's wealth (vv. 35-36), with Egypt itself begging them to leave. The Exodus narrative's dramatic reversal — from humiliation to exaltation, from few to many, from poor to wealthy — is a pattern that the NT applies to Christ's death and resurrection.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>vayisa ha'am et-beseto</strong>: 'the people carried their dough on their shoulders.' The kneading troughs (<em>mishtarotam</em>) were wrapped in clothing and carried — because they could not delay to leaven the bread. This is the factual origin of the <em>matzot</em> that would be baked at Sukkoth: the unleavened bread is not merely commanded but physically produced by the urgency of the departure. The hasty exit embeds the theology into the material circumstance: redemption comes without delay and cannot wait for the ordinary processes of life to complete themselves.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>uvenei Yisrael asu kidvar Moshe vayish'alu meiMitzrayim</strong>: 'the Israelites did as Moses instructed and asked of the Egyptians.' The plundering of Egypt fulfills YHWH's promise to Abraham in Gen 15:14: 'afterward they shall come out with great possessions (<em>rechush gadol</em>).' Israel takes <em>keli-keseph u-chelei zahav u-semalot</em> (articles of silver, gold, and clothing) — the material wealth of the ancient world's most prosperous nation. Paul interprets this in the Spirit: the spoiling of Egypt is a type of all truth belonging to the church and being reclaimed from the &ldquo;Egypt&rdquo; of pagan culture (the Alexandrian tradition of theological use of pagan philosophy drew on this).</p>",
    "36": "<p><strong>vaYHWH natan et-chen ha'am beynei Mitzrayim vayash'ilum</strong>: 'YHWH gave the people favor in the eyes of Egypt, and they gave them what they asked.' The <em>chen</em> YHWH sovereignly provided (cf. 11:3) was the instrument of the plundering. <em>Vayenatzelu et-Mitzrayim</em>: 'they plundered Egypt' — the Piel of <em>natsal</em> (to strip, rescue) used in a plundering context. The same verb is used in 3:22 and 12:35 — YHWH promised the spoiling, Moses announced it, and now it occurs. The plundering of Egypt is the material accompaniment of the spiritual liberation: the enslaved gain not only freedom but the material means to build the tabernacle in the wilderness.</p>",
    "37": "<p><strong>shesh meot elef ragley hagevarin</strong>: 'about 600,000 men on foot.' The number has generated enormous scholarly discussion: if 600,000 men (adult males), the total population including women and children would be 2-3 million — an enormous number for the Sinai wilderness. Some scholars read <em>eleph</em> (H505) not as 1,000 but as a military unit of variable size (suggesting ~5,550-6,000 men total), following George Mendenhall's analysis. The narrative's point is clear regardless of the exact count: Israel left Egypt as a nation, not a family. The 600,000 figure also connects to the census in Numbers 1-2 (603,550 men), creating a coherent numerology for the wilderness generation.</p>",
    "38": "<p><strong>veGam erev rav ala itam</strong>: 'a mixed multitude also went up with them.' The <em>erev rav</em> (mixed multitude, H6154) accompanying Israel is the first indication that the Exodus was not ethnically exclusive: non-Israelites joined the departure. The same group is later blamed for the craving of meat (Num 11:4: <em>ve'asafsuf asher beqirbo</em>). The <em>erev rav</em> may have included other Semitic slaves, Egyptians married to Israelites, or people drawn by YHWH's power. The principle of the mixed multitude joining Israel prefigures Ruth, Rahab, and the Gentile inclusion in the covenant community.</p>",
    "39": "<p><strong>ki lo chametz ki-gerushim miMitzrayim velo yachlu lehitmahmeah</strong>: 'for it was not leavened because they were expelled from Egypt and could not delay.' The physical reason for the unleavened bread is provided: there was no time to leaven it. The haste of the departure is the empirical origin of the theological requirement. The connection between urgency and unleavened bread is made explicit: the <em>matzot</em> that Israel eats at Passover every year is the bread of urgent departure — the bread of those who cannot linger in the old life because the new creation calls them forward.</p>",
    "40": "<p><strong>umoshav benei Yisrael asher yashvu beMitzrayim shloshim shanah ve'arba meot shanah</strong>: '430 years.' The 430-year sojourn in Egypt (from the LXX version, extended to include time in Canaan: 'the sojourn ... in Egypt and Canaan') is cited by Paul in Gal 3:17: 'the law, which came 430 years afterward, does not annul a covenant previously ratified by God.' Paul's use confirms the 430-year figure and connects it to the Abrahamic covenant timeline: the Sinai law came 430 years after Abraham, not 430 years after the entry to Egypt (supporting the LXX's longer reckoning). The precision of the period — <em>vayehiy mikets shloshim shanah ve'arba meot shanah</em> (at the end of 430 years, to the very day) — emphasizes YHWH's absolute control over the timing of the Exodus.</p>",
    "41": "<p><strong>tzivot YHWH</strong> (armies of YHWH): Israel leaves Egypt not as a refugee crowd but as <em>tzivot YHWH</em> — YHWH's military forces. The same term (<em>tzva'ot</em>, hosts/armies) is the root of the divine name <em>YHWH Tzvaot</em> (YHWH of Hosts/Armies), one of the most frequent divine names in the OT prophets. The exodus is a military event: YHWH is the commander, Israel is the army, and the exit from Egypt is a march. This militarized framing of the Exodus is the background for Ephesians 6's armor of God — the Christian life is framed within the same exodus-march-warfare structure.</p>",
    "42": "<p><strong>leil shimmurim hu l'YHWH</strong>: 'a night of keeping/vigil for YHWH' — <em>shimmurim</em> (H8107, from <em>shamar</em>, to keep, guard) describes the night as one of active divine vigilance. YHWH keeps watch over his people on this night of all nights — the very night he acts to deliver them. The double use of <em>shimmurim</em> ('a night of vigil for YHWH to bring them out ... this same night is a night of vigil for YHWH for all the Israelites throughout their generations') frames both the original event and its annual commemoration as acts of reciprocal watching: YHWH watches over Israel, Israel watches through the night. The NT's night-vigil eschatology (Matt 25:13: keep watch; Luke 12:37: blessed are those servants whom the master finds awake) draws on the <em>leil shimmurim</em> pattern.</p>",
    "43": "<p><strong>zot chuqat hapesach</strong>: 'this is the regulation of the Passover.' The Passover regulations (vv. 43-50) address participation eligibility: the central criterion is circumcision (<em>mila</em>). <em>Kol-ben-nechar lo-yochal bo</em>: 'no foreigner (lit. son of a foreign people) shall eat of it.' The restriction is covenant-based, not ethnic: the <em>ben-nechar</em> is distinguished from the <em>ger</em> (resident alien, v. 48) who may eat if circumcised. The circumcision requirement makes the covenant sign the entry point for Passover participation — covenant membership precedes covenant meal.</p>",
    "44": "<p><strong>ve'eved ish miqnat-keseph</strong>: 'a slave purchased with money' — a permanent household slave (<em>eved</em>) who has been circumcised may eat the Passover. The contrast with the hired worker (<em>toshav ve'sachir</em>, v. 45) who may not eat reflects the distinction between full household membership (the slave belongs to the household permanently) and transient engagement. The slave's circumcision integrates him into the covenant community. Paul's use of slave imagery for the Christian's relationship to Christ (Rom 6:18-22; 1 Cor 7:22) draws on this covenant-household logic: belonging to Christ means full participation in the covenant meal.</p>",
    "45": "<p><strong>toshav vesachir lo-yochal bo</strong>: 'a temporary resident and a hired worker may not eat of it.' The <em>toshav</em> (sojourner, resident alien without permanent status) and the <em>sachir</em> (hired worker, day laborer) are excluded — their relationship to the household is temporary and transactional, not covenantal. This verse creates the distinction that v. 48's exception clarifies: a resident foreigner who submits to circumcision transitions from <em>toshav</em> to full covenant member. The line between inclusion and exclusion is the covenant sign, not ethnicity.</p>",
    "46": "<p><strong>veetzem lo tishberu-bo</strong>: 'you shall not break a bone of it.' The prohibition against breaking the Passover lamb's bones (also in Num 9:12) is cited in John 19:36 as fulfilled when the soldiers did not break Jesus's legs: 'these things took place that the Scripture might be fulfilled: not one of his bones will be broken.' The unbroken-bone requirement for the Passover lamb is one of the most precise typological fulfillments in the NT. The physical integrity of the lamb corresponds to the physical integrity of Christ's body — the true Passover lamb. Ps 34:20 ('he keeps all his bones; not one of them is broken') applies the bone-protection language to the righteous man, which John also sees fulfilled in Jesus.</p>",
    "47": "<p><strong>kol-adat Yisrael ya'asu oto</strong>: 'the whole congregation of Israel shall keep it.' The Passover is a community-wide obligation — not optional, not individual. The <em>edah</em> (congregation, assembly) is the technical term for the covenant community gathered. The communal nature of the Passover meal is its fundamental character: no individual participates alone; the whole covenant community celebrates together. This community-wide structure is the background for Paul's 'the cup of blessing that we bless, is it not a participation in the blood of Christ? The bread that we break, is it not a participation in the body of Christ? Because there is one bread, we who are many are one body' (1 Cor 10:16-17).</p>",
    "48": "<p><strong>vechi-yagur itcha ger ve'asa pesach l'YHWH himol lo chol-zachur</strong>: 'if a stranger dwells with you and wants to keep the Passover to YHWH, he must have all the males circumcised.' The inclusion of the circumcised foreigner (<em>ger</em>) in the Passover community is the proto-Gentile inclusion: the covenant meal is open to those who receive the covenant sign. This verse becomes a NT proof-text for Gentile inclusion: Paul argues in Gal 3:8 that Abraham's covenant was always designed to include the nations, and the circumcision requirement has been replaced by faith in Christ (Gal 3:26-29: 'in Christ Jesus you are all sons of God through faith ... neither Jew nor Greek').</p>",
    "49": "<p><strong>torah achat yihyeh laezrach velager</strong>: 'the same law shall apply to the native and to the stranger.' The principle of equal legal standing for the native and the resident alien is stated explicitly — one law (<em>torah achat</em>), not a two-tier system. This principle appears repeatedly in the Torah (Lev 24:22; Num 9:14; 15:15-16) and is foundational to the NT abolition of Jewish-Gentile distinction in the church: 'for there is no distinction between Jew and Greek' (Rom 10:12); 'there is neither Jew nor Greek, slave nor free, male nor female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28).</p>",
    "50": "<p><strong>vaya'asu kol-benei Yisrael ka'asher tzivah YHWH</strong>: 'all the Israelites did just as YHWH had commanded.' The compliance formula closes the Passover instruction section. The emphasis on full obedience (<em>kol-benei Yisrael</em>, all Israel) and precision (<em>ka'asher tzivah YHWH</em>, exactly as YHWH commanded) frames the Exodus as a covenant-keeping event: Israel's obedience to the Passover instructions is the faith-act that receives YHWH's protection. The same pattern — hearing the word, doing it precisely — underlies the NT's 'faith that works' (James 2:17-18) and Jesus's parable of the two builders (Matt 7:24-27).</p>",
    "51": "<p><strong>vayehiy betzem hayom hazeh hotzi YHWH et-benei Yisrael mei'eretz Mitzrayim al-tzivotam</strong>: 'on that very day YHWH brought the Israelites out of Egypt by their divisions.' <em>Betzem hayom hazeh</em> ('on this very day') — the phrase used throughout the Exodus for the precision of divine timing (also in v. 17, 41). The book of Exodus closes its narrative of the departure with this summary: YHWH is the subject, Israel is the object, and the movement is out from Egypt. The phrase <em>al-tzivotam</em> ('by their divisions/armies') repeats the military framing of v. 41 — Israel leaves as YHWH's organized military force, not as a chaotic mass. The Exodus is a completed, organized, divinely orchestrated event.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "2": "<p><strong>anochi YHWH eloheicha asher hotzeiticha meeretz mitzraim mibeit avadim</strong>: 'I am YHWH your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of slavery.' The Decalogue opens not with a command but with a redemption narrative — the commands follow from the prior act of grace. YHWH does not say 'obey me so that I will be your God and bring you out' but 'I brought you out; therefore I am your God; therefore obey.' The evangelical-imperative structure of the Decalogue is: grace, then obligation. Paul's ethical sections follow the same pattern: Romans 1-11 (gospel), then 12-16 (imperatives); Galatians 1-4 (grace), then 5-6 (walk).</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "9": "<p><strong>kekol asher ani mareeh otcha et tabnit hamishkan veet tabnit kol kelav veken taashu</strong>: 'Exactly as I show you concerning the pattern [<em>tabnit</em>] of the tabernacle, and of all its furniture, so you shall make it.' The Hebrew <em>tabnit</em> (pattern/model) implies the earthly tabernacle is a copy of a heavenly original. Hebrews (8:5) quotes this verse explicitly (using LXX <em>typos</em> — pattern, type) to argue that the Levitical priests serve a copy and shadow of the heavenly things. The tabernacle's typological function is not a later Christian imposition but is built into the original instructions: Moses saw the heavenly original; Israel built the earthly copy.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "6": "<p><strong>YHWH YHWH el rachum vechanun erech apayim verav chesed veemet</strong>: 'YHWH YHWH, a God merciful and gracious, slow to anger, and abounding in steadfast love [<em>chesed</em>] and faithfulness [<em>emet</em>].' The thirteen attributes of divine mercy (mid-dot harachamim) became a cornerstone of Jewish liturgical theology, recited on fast days and festivals. <em>Chesed</em> (covenant love, steadfast love, lovingkindness) is perhaps the OT's richest theological term — it combines loyalty, love, mercy, and covenant-faithfulness into a single word. John's 'grace and truth' (John 1:14, 17) is likely a translation of <em>chesed veemet</em>, applying Exod 34:6's divine attributes to the incarnate Word.</p>"
  }
}

CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "11": "<p>The historical context of the Exodus is debated: the most common evangelical dating places the Exodus ca. 1446 BCE (the 'early date,' based on 1 Kings 6:1's 480 years from Exodus to Solomon's temple ca. 966 BCE), during Thutmose III's reign. The 'late date' (ca. 1270-1250 BCE, during Ramesses II's reign) is favored by many archaeologists based on the cities Pithom and Ramesses mentioned in Exod 1:11. The Merneptah Stele (ca. 1208 BCE) mentions Israel as a people already in Canaan, providing a terminus ad quem. The question remains open; the theological significance of the Exodus is independent of the exact date.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The Passover (Heb. <em>pesach</em>) became the foundational festival of Israelite identity — the annual re-enactment and remembrance of YHWH's redemptive act. The Passover Seder developed in the Second Temple period and was the meal Jesus shared with his disciples on the night of his arrest. Jesus's identification of the cup with his blood and the bread with his body (Luke 22:19-20) reinterprets the Passover meal through the lens of his approaching death: the new exodus is accomplished through his death as the new Passover lamb. Paul's 'Christ our Passover has been sacrificed' (1 Cor 5:7) is the theological crystallization of this identification.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>The Sinai covenant is the central structuring event of the OT: it establishes the constitutional framework of Israel's relationship with YHWH. Its suzerainty-treaty structure (parallel to Hittite treaties: preamble, historical prologue, stipulations, blessings/curses, witnesses) places YHWH as the great king and Israel as his vassal. The Decalogue (20:1-17) is the covenant's summary stipulations. The Book of the Covenant (20:22-23:33) elaborates case law. The covenant-inauguration ceremony (24:1-11) seals the relationship with blood and a covenant meal. Hebrews 12:18-24 contrasts the terrors of Sinai with the joy of Zion — the old covenant's thunders and fire point forward to the new covenant's completed mediation in Christ.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>The tabernacle instructions (Exod 25-31) and their execution (35-40) occupy more chapters in Exodus than any other section. The tabernacle is the theological center of the wilderness narrative: YHWH's presence (kavod) dwelling among Israel in the portable sanctuary. Its structure (outer court, holy place, most holy place) reflects the graduated holiness of sacred space that culminates in the ark and mercy seat where YHWH meets with Israel. Solomon's temple is the permanent version of this portable structure. The NT develops the typological chain: tabernacle → temple → Christ's body (John 2:21) → the church as temple (1 Cor 3:16) → the new Jerusalem as the final dwelling of God with his people (Rev 21:3).</p>"
  }
}

CHRIST = {
  "12": {
    "13": "<p>A fulfillment: 'When I see the blood, I will pass over you, and no plague will befall you to destroy you when I strike the land of Egypt.' The Passover blood on the doorposts is the OT's most developed type of substitutionary atonement: an innocent lamb dies; its blood marks the household; the destroyer passes over those marked. Paul makes the typological identification explicit: 'Christ our Passover has been sacrificed' (1 Cor 5:7). John structures his Gospel so the crucifixion occurs when the Passover lambs are being slaughtered in the temple (John 19:14), and notes the non-breaking of bones fulfills Exod 12:46. The Passover is not merely a historical parallel but the interpretive key YHWH planted in Israel's annual liturgy to explain, centuries in advance, the theological meaning of the cross.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "22": "<p>A type: 'And the people of Israel went into the midst of the sea on dry ground, the waters being a wall to them on their right hand and on their left.' Paul explicitly calls the Red Sea crossing a baptismal type: 'all were baptized into Moses in the cloud and in the sea' (1 Cor 10:1-2). The structure is identical to Christian baptism: God's redemptive act through a threshold of water, from slavery into freedom, into covenant relationship. But the antitype is greater: baptism into Christ is death and resurrection with Christ (Rom 6:3-4), not merely deliverance from one earthly power. Moses led Israel through the sea; Christ leads his people through death itself.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "15": "<p>A type: 'It is manna' (or 'What is it?') — bread from heaven that YHWH provides. Jesus in John 6 identifies himself as the fulfillment of the manna type: 'Your fathers ate the manna in the wilderness, and they died. This is the bread that comes down from heaven, so that one may eat of it and not die. I am the living bread that came down from heaven' (John 6:49-51). The typological contrast is sharp: the manna sustained physical life temporarily; Christ gives eternal life. The manna was perishable; Christ is permanent. The manna was provided daily; Christ is given once. The Lord's Supper as ongoing eating of Christ (John 6:53-56) is the enacted fulfillment of the manna's promise.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "22": "<p>A type: 'There I will meet with you, and from above the mercy seat, from between the two cherubim that are on the ark of the testimony, I will speak with you.' The mercy seat (<em>kapporet</em>, from <em>kipper</em>, to atone/cover) is the lid of the ark, sprinkled with blood on Yom Kippur. Paul in Romans 3:25 calls Christ a <em>hilasterion</em> — the LXX word for the mercy seat. Christ is both the priest who offers the sacrifice and the mercy seat on which the blood is placed; he is both offerer and the place of offering, the one who makes atonement and the locus where God and humanity meet. The tabernacle's most restricted and holy object — accessible only once a year, only by the high priest, only with blood — is fulfilled in Christ who provides permanent access to God.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('exodus')
    merge_echo(e, ECHO)
    save_echo('exodus', e)

    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'exodus', c)

    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', c)

    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus')
